00:11:04.086 --> 00:11:06.046 A:middle
So this was an awesome
puzzle game.

00:11:06.046 --> 00:11:09.016 A:middle
And it's kind of the
perfect example here to use

00:11:09.016 --> 00:11:10.956 A:middle
as an onboarding case study.

00:11:11.436 --> 00:11:15.156 A:middle
So right away what you see here
is they're using coaching tips

00:11:15.206 --> 00:11:18.076 A:middle
to explain the goal,
which is to deliver candy

00:11:18.076 --> 00:11:19.456 A:middle
to Om Nom, the little character.

00:11:20.356 --> 00:11:22.556 A:middle
And then they start to
tell you about things

00:11:22.556 --> 00:11:24.186 A:middle
like the primary interaction.

00:11:24.246 --> 00:11:25.576 A:middle
In "Cut the Rope", you swipe

00:11:25.736 --> 00:11:27.216 A:middle
with your finger
to cut the rope.

00:11:27.746 --> 00:11:30.016 A:middle
Now you might be looking at
this kind of going like, well,

00:11:30.016 --> 00:11:30.926 A:middle
that's totally obvious.

00:11:31.376 --> 00:11:33.776 A:middle
But, no, it's only because
you've seen this picture.

00:11:34.146 --> 00:11:38.426 A:middle
And so the, you know what
people would do without this,

00:11:38.426 --> 00:11:41.656 A:middle
they would tap the candy,
they would tap Om Nom trying

00:11:41.656 --> 00:11:43.596 A:middle
to get him to jump
up and eat the candy.

00:11:43.596 --> 00:11:44.576 A:middle
They don't know what to do.

00:11:44.916 --> 00:11:46.836 A:middle
And those aren't the
right interactions, right?

00:11:46.876 --> 00:11:49.646 A:middle
The correct one is to
swipe, cut the rope.

00:11:50.396 --> 00:11:53.526 A:middle
So then once the
player has that down,

00:11:53.526 --> 00:11:56.446 A:middle
then they start introducing new
interactions one at that time.

00:11:56.916 --> 00:11:58.866 A:middle
So each time there's
another coaching tip.

00:11:59.276 --> 00:12:03.126 A:middle
So here you cut the rope,
the candy flows down,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:59.276 --> 00:12:03.126 A:middle
So here you cut the rope,
the candy flows down,

00:12:03.126 --> 00:12:04.156 A:middle
it goes into the bubble,

00:12:04.156 --> 00:12:06.216 A:middle
and then the bubble will
start to lift it up.

00:12:06.686 --> 00:12:09.946 A:middle
And then there's another tip
put right in context once

00:12:09.986 --> 00:12:12.726 A:middle
that happens telling the
player to pop the bubble

00:12:12.726 --> 00:12:15.456 A:middle
with their finger and
that will release it

00:12:15.456 --> 00:12:17.626 A:middle
and it will come down to Om Nom.

00:12:18.236 --> 00:12:23.426 A:middle
Okay. And then more really
sort of subtle thing is

00:12:23.426 --> 00:12:27.906 A:middle
that a big part of the
gameplay in Cut the Rope comes

00:12:27.966 --> 00:12:30.456 A:middle
from trying to get the candy

00:12:30.456 --> 00:12:35.566 A:middle
to touch all the stars before
it gets down to Om Nom and kind

00:12:35.566 --> 00:12:36.926 A:middle
of routing around that way.

00:12:36.926 --> 00:12:40.166 A:middle
And to be successful at that
usually takes some trial

00:12:40.166 --> 00:12:41.526 A:middle
and error on every level

00:12:41.766 --> 00:12:42.906 A:middle
when you're actually
playing the game.

00:12:43.226 --> 00:12:46.946 A:middle
So it's actually really
important to the Core Loop

00:12:46.946 --> 00:12:52.196 A:middle
of this game to show players
how they can try again, right.

00:12:52.196 --> 00:12:55.976 A:middle
So in their onboarding, they
call that out specifically.

00:12:55.976 --> 00:12:57.996 A:middle
And you would think oh,
that's just, you know,

00:12:57.996 --> 00:12:59.856 A:middle
okay fine they're showing
me around the buttons.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:00.236 --> 00:13:03.306 A:middle
But, no, if they had left
that to the player to discover

00:13:03.306 --> 00:13:05.756 A:middle
on their own, some people
might not have played

00:13:05.756 --> 00:13:08.666 A:middle
around with all the buttons and
the menus to go and play again.

00:13:08.666 --> 00:13:10.896 A:middle
But really this is
core to the gameplay

00:13:11.066 --> 00:13:13.956 A:middle
so that's why they show it.

00:13:14.286 --> 00:13:15.636 A:middle
But, okay, so to summarize now:

00:13:16.236 --> 00:13:19.876 A:middle
So start by bringing the
player right into the game

00:13:19.876 --> 00:13:21.546 A:middle
and show them how
to get started.

00:13:21.546 --> 00:13:25.386 A:middle
And then introduce more complex
interactions one at that time.

00:13:26.136 --> 00:13:28.806 A:middle
Provide tips and
context as you go along

00:13:28.806 --> 00:13:32.726 A:middle
and then help them discover the
things that will be important

00:13:32.726 --> 00:13:34.636 A:middle
in the game as they
play through it.

00:13:35.046 --> 00:13:36.926 A:middle
So that's number two:
be a good teacher.

00:13:37.776 --> 00:13:41.166 A:middle
Now, I want to mention, also,
we're having a related session.

00:13:41.166 --> 00:13:43.506 A:middle
It's going to be on
Thursday, very aptly named,

00:13:43.886 --> 00:13:46.866 A:middle
"Making a Great First Impression
with Strong Onboarding Design".

00:13:46.866 --> 00:13:49.456 A:middle
We'll spend a whole hour
going through some examples

00:13:49.456 --> 00:13:50.956 A:middle
that really get this right.

00:13:50.956 --> 00:13:52.606 A:middle
So be sure to catch
that on Thursday.

00:13:53.746 --> 00:13:57.816 A:middle
All right, now I want to turn
focus to the gameplay itself.

00:13:57.816 --> 00:14:02.116 A:middle
So number three is to really
tune and perfect your Core Loop.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:57.816 --> 00:14:02.116 A:middle
So number three is to really
tune and perfect your Core Loop.

00:14:02.116 --> 00:14:04.366 A:middle
You know, I talk to
people all the time.

00:14:04.366 --> 00:14:06.996 A:middle
And people will ask me to
take a look at their game,

00:14:06.996 --> 00:14:09.206 A:middle
give them some feedback, you
know stuff under development.

00:14:09.726 --> 00:14:12.486 A:middle
And a lot of times what I'm
looking at is something,

00:14:12.486 --> 00:14:15.716 A:middle
you know, they're saying, I just
it doesn't really feel fun yet.

00:14:16.156 --> 00:14:19.446 A:middle
And what that really comes
down to is the Core Loop.

00:14:20.316 --> 00:14:23.126 A:middle
So Core Loop is the
term that wraps up how

00:14:23.126 --> 00:14:25.786 A:middle
to describe the game mechanic
in terms of, you know,

00:14:25.786 --> 00:14:27.836 A:middle
the actions the player
takes in the game;

00:14:28.106 --> 00:14:30.916 A:middle
the reward that they
receive, you know,

00:14:30.916 --> 00:14:35.816 A:middle
as they're pursuing a goal;
and the resulting expansion

00:14:35.816 --> 00:14:40.086 A:middle
of the game or the growth of the
character that motivated them

00:14:40.086 --> 00:14:41.236 A:middle
to pursue that reward.

00:14:42.056 --> 00:14:44.396 A:middle
And just in games that
aren't quite right,

00:14:44.536 --> 00:14:46.996 A:middle
what I often find is that
there's some disconnect

00:14:46.996 --> 00:14:51.026 A:middle
in this cycle or some
mismatch between the parts

00:14:51.466 --> 00:14:52.796 A:middle
so they don't really
line up well.

00:14:53.556 --> 00:14:55.386 A:middle
But, so let me just
illustrate this

00:14:55.426 --> 00:14:58.576 A:middle
by showing you some typical
examples from different genres,

00:14:58.576 --> 00:14:59.746 A:middle
just to set the stage.

00:14:59.746 --> 00:15:02.326 A:middle
So, you know, here is a
fantasy role playing game.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:59.746 --> 00:15:02.326 A:middle
So, you know, here is a
fantasy role playing game.

00:15:02.646 --> 00:15:05.046 A:middle
I explore the dungeon.

00:15:05.046 --> 00:15:06.746 A:middle
I fight enemies.

00:15:06.746 --> 00:15:09.676 A:middle
Defeating the enemies gets
me treasure and experience.

00:15:10.206 --> 00:15:12.706 A:middle
And then I use that
treasure and experience

00:15:12.706 --> 00:15:15.306 A:middle
to level up and to buy things.

00:15:15.306 --> 00:15:17.236 A:middle
And then that lets
me go and fight more

00:15:17.236 --> 00:15:18.786 A:middle
and more powerful enemies, okay?

00:15:18.786 --> 00:15:19.336 A:middle
Very clear.

00:15:20.426 --> 00:15:23.296 A:middle
Or a platformer, you know, the
basic idea in a platformer is

00:15:23.296 --> 00:15:25.616 A:middle
to run and jump, okay,
that's the player action.

00:15:25.966 --> 00:15:28.616 A:middle
But their goal is really to
complete the level itself

00:15:28.616 --> 00:15:31.086 A:middle
and avoid all the
obstacles and the bad guys

00:15:31.086 --> 00:15:33.336 A:middle
and collect the stars
or power ups

00:15:33.336 --> 00:15:35.166 A:middle
or whatever is happening
on that level.

00:15:35.726 --> 00:15:38.616 A:middle
But then if you're
successful the expansion is

00:15:38.616 --> 00:15:42.106 A:middle
to unlock the next stage,
literally expand the universe,

00:15:42.106 --> 00:15:44.216 A:middle
the game universe,
for that game.

00:15:44.666 --> 00:15:47.796 A:middle
And where then you then go
and find new things to run

00:15:47.796 --> 00:15:50.786 A:middle
and jump over, new
obstacles, and so on.

00:15:50.846 --> 00:15:51.186 A:middle
But, okay.

00:15:51.186 --> 00:15:54.006 A:middle
So now to get a little
deeper, you know,

00:15:54.006 --> 00:15:56.686 A:middle
it's really worth
noting that some

00:15:56.686 --> 00:15:58.816 A:middle
of the most compelling
games are the ones

00:15:59.086 --> 00:16:01.066 A:middle
with more than one Core Loop.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:59.086 --> 00:16:01.066 A:middle
with more than one Core Loop.

00:16:01.466 --> 00:16:03.136 A:middle
And I'm showing these
side by side.

00:16:03.236 --> 00:16:05.516 A:middle
But really they're
meant to be overlapping.

00:16:05.866 --> 00:16:07.546 A:middle
So you're fighting monsters,

00:16:07.546 --> 00:16:09.146 A:middle
you gain experience,
you're leveling up.

00:16:09.206 --> 00:16:12.126 A:middle
But, at the same time,
you're collecting clues.

00:16:12.126 --> 00:16:14.356 A:middle
You're using the clues
to solve a puzzle.

00:16:14.646 --> 00:16:16.676 A:middle
The puzzle lets you
unlock a door.

00:16:16.716 --> 00:16:19.686 A:middle
Behind the door there's more
monsters and more clues.

00:16:19.686 --> 00:16:23.276 A:middle
And these are overlaid in the
experience on top of each other.

00:16:23.886 --> 00:16:25.186 A:middle
But, okay.

00:16:25.396 --> 00:16:28.996 A:middle
So let me give you some
more concrete advice here.

00:16:28.996 --> 00:16:31.356 A:middle
So, you know, what
really is the bottom line?

00:16:31.696 --> 00:16:36.176 A:middle
So the best games, first,
are the ones that really,

00:16:37.036 --> 00:16:40.576 A:middle
clearly understand their
target audience and are able

00:16:40.576 --> 00:16:43.416 A:middle
to put center excuse
me, put the centerpoint

00:16:43.416 --> 00:16:46.686 A:middle
of the Core Loop right
on top of that audience.

00:16:47.786 --> 00:16:51.186 A:middle
And it's important that the Core
Loop be easy to express and kind

00:16:51.186 --> 00:16:52.326 A:middle
of easy to understand.

00:16:52.326 --> 00:16:54.196 A:middle
That's kind of, when
I find games

00:16:54.576 --> 00:16:57.956 A:middle
that are have these little
mismatches, usually it's a case

00:16:57.956 --> 00:16:59.756 A:middle
where it's difficult
for the developer

00:16:59.756 --> 00:17:02.906 A:middle
to actually express the
Core Loop, these components,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:59.756 --> 00:17:02.906 A:middle
to actually express the
Core Loop, these components,

00:17:02.936 --> 00:17:06.175 A:middle
clearly in terms of the action,
the reward, the expansion.

00:17:07.455 --> 00:17:09.806 A:middle
Now, as I have been
saying, make sure each phase

00:17:09.806 --> 00:17:12.746 A:middle
of this feeds right
into the next.

00:17:12.746 --> 00:17:15.016 A:middle
And, sort of, all of the
energy that the player gives

00:17:15.016 --> 00:17:17.726 A:middle
into one part of it flows
around and, kind of,

00:17:17.726 --> 00:17:19.266 A:middle
reinforces the other parts.

00:17:20.566 --> 00:17:23.286 A:middle
Make each iteration meaningful.

00:17:23.286 --> 00:17:25.336 A:middle
And I'll talk about this
a little more as I talk

00:17:25.336 --> 00:17:27.286 A:middle
about progression in the game.

00:17:27.906 --> 00:17:30.866 A:middle
But then also question
your assumptions.

00:17:30.866 --> 00:17:33.696 A:middle
And this is probably the best
advice for any developer is

00:17:33.696 --> 00:17:37.346 A:middle
to go back and really
rethink it and keep iterating

00:17:37.346 --> 00:17:39.696 A:middle
until you know you've
done it well.

00:17:40.326 --> 00:17:42.406 A:middle
And, you know, how do you know?

00:17:42.406 --> 00:17:43.546 A:middle
How do you really know?

00:17:43.546 --> 00:17:47.396 A:middle
I could say playtest, but
that's just a punt, right.

00:17:47.396 --> 00:17:51.256 A:middle
It's like, how do you really
know that you did it well?

00:17:52.036 --> 00:17:56.026 A:middle
Well, you know it by really
thinking it through yourself.

00:17:56.556 --> 00:17:59.336 A:middle
You know, if you find the
clues, will you be able

00:17:59.336 --> 00:18:02.666 A:middle
to solve the puzzle without
some giant leap of faith


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:59.336 --> 00:18:02.666 A:middle
to solve the puzzle without
some giant leap of faith

00:18:02.666 --> 00:18:06.276 A:middle
or going online to Google how
to figure out this puzzle.

00:18:07.156 --> 00:18:10.676 A:middle
Well, you know, if you unlock
something, if you solve

00:18:10.676 --> 00:18:13.386 A:middle
that puzzle, is it going
to unlock the next stage?

00:18:13.716 --> 00:18:16.576 A:middle
If you unlock that next stage,
will I have something new

00:18:16.576 --> 00:18:18.926 A:middle
or novel to really look
at once I get there?

00:18:19.666 --> 00:18:20.956 A:middle
Okay. So test it.

00:18:21.766 --> 00:18:25.046 A:middle
But, at the same time,
don't feel boxed in.

00:18:25.416 --> 00:18:27.326 A:middle
I am not saying that
every game needs

00:18:27.326 --> 00:18:31.576 A:middle
to follow the same design
methodology or, you know,

00:18:31.576 --> 00:18:34.226 A:middle
kind of deal with its
audience in the same way.

00:18:34.576 --> 00:18:36.906 A:middle
A lot of the really
best expressions

00:18:37.076 --> 00:18:40.706 A:middle
of great games are the ones that
aren't afraid to mix this up.

00:18:41.226 --> 00:18:45.166 A:middle
But, so, now, let me show
you just a quick example,

00:18:45.986 --> 00:18:47.786 A:middle
a game that's really
fantastic in the way

00:18:47.786 --> 00:18:50.376 A:middle
that it does its Core Loop is
the Apple Design Award winner

00:18:50.376 --> 00:18:53.046 A:middle
last year, this is "Ridiculous
Fishing" by Vlambeer.

00:18:53.626 --> 00:18:56.806 A:middle
So it really has, I
think you could break it

00:18:56.806 --> 00:18:58.976 A:middle
down into three distinct
mechanics.

00:18:59.256 --> 00:19:03.216 A:middle
The first one is when you
are dropping your line


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:59.256 --> 00:19:03.216 A:middle
The first one is when you
are dropping your line

00:19:03.216 --> 00:19:03.926 A:middle
into the water.

00:19:03.926 --> 00:19:06.566 A:middle
You're just trying to, you're
using the accelerometer

00:19:06.566 --> 00:19:08.456 A:middle
or the gyroscope and
trying to get the line

00:19:08.456 --> 00:19:10.896 A:middle
down through the water
avoiding the fish,

00:19:11.016 --> 00:19:12.326 A:middle
get it as deep as you can.

00:19:12.466 --> 00:19:16.576 A:middle
Okay. Then once you run out
of line or once you hit a fish

00:19:16.576 --> 00:19:19.186 A:middle
on the way down,
everything reverses.

00:19:19.186 --> 00:19:21.976 A:middle
And now you're going
back up and reeling

00:19:21.976 --> 00:19:23.766 A:middle
in as many fish as you can.

00:19:24.096 --> 00:19:27.846 A:middle
We're back on the gyro again
and just trying now to collect

00:19:27.936 --> 00:19:29.576 A:middle
as many of the fish
and try to run

00:19:29.616 --> 00:19:31.776 A:middle
into them while avoiding
the jellyfish

00:19:31.776 --> 00:19:33.156 A:middle
and other baddies
that are there.

00:19:33.206 --> 00:19:37.716 A:middle
And then the third loop, when
we get up to the surface,

00:19:37.716 --> 00:19:42.146 A:middle
of course, we fling the fish up
into the air and then you tap

00:19:42.286 --> 00:19:44.836 A:middle
on them to shoot them
out of the sky, right,

00:19:45.146 --> 00:19:46.756 A:middle
so and collect points.

00:19:47.616 --> 00:19:50.936 A:middle
And so, and then those
points are what we use

00:19:51.506 --> 00:19:53.066 A:middle
as the expansion in the game.

00:19:53.066 --> 00:19:56.856 A:middle
It lets us get a better lure,
a longer line, and so on.

00:19:56.856 --> 00:19:59.356 A:middle
And so the game is really,
you know, hilarious.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:20:00.046 --> 00:20:00.966 A:middle
And if you didn't
see it last year

00:20:00.966 --> 00:20:03.646 A:middle
from the design awards,
check it out.

00:20:03.916 --> 00:20:05.876 A:middle
But so that's tuning
your Core Loop.

00:20:07.666 --> 00:20:09.876 A:middle
Now, let me expand
out from there.

00:20:10.186 --> 00:20:13.726 A:middle
And so for the next few parts
of the talk, I want to go

00:20:13.726 --> 00:20:17.766 A:middle
through some aspects of this
next ring around the Core Loop

00:20:18.036 --> 00:20:20.736 A:middle
and I want to start with
the interaction mechanic.

00:20:20.736 --> 00:20:22.756 A:middle
Because obviously, you know,
how the player interacts

00:20:22.756 --> 00:20:25.296 A:middle
with your game is completely
fundamental to the success

00:20:25.806 --> 00:20:27.346 A:middle
of the Core Loop,
to it feeling fun.

00:20:27.956 --> 00:20:30.906 A:middle
And if your players seem
to be having trouble

00:20:30.906 --> 00:20:33.286 A:middle
with the controls,
this is where to start.

00:20:34.006 --> 00:20:36.506 A:middle
And it's to design for touch.

00:20:37.296 --> 00:20:38.836 A:middle
So sometimes when I'm working

00:20:38.836 --> 00:20:41.246 A:middle
with someone who's
bringing a game over to iOS

00:20:41.446 --> 00:20:45.026 A:middle
from another platform like a
PC or a console or whatever,

00:20:45.346 --> 00:20:49.006 A:middle
their first instinct is actually
to just bring their Core Loop

00:20:49.006 --> 00:20:52.606 A:middle
over completely unchanged,
you know, including all

00:20:52.606 --> 00:20:54.996 A:middle
of their old interaction
mechanic, right.

00:20:54.996 --> 00:20:58.166 A:middle
And so, you know, if their game
was based on pressing buttons

00:20:58.216 --> 00:21:00.016 A:middle
than they just overlay
the screen,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:20:58.216 --> 00:21:00.016 A:middle
than they just overlay
the screen,

00:21:00.016 --> 00:21:01.176 A:middle
superimpose some buttons.

00:21:02.026 --> 00:21:05.006 A:middle
Or if they used to use a
D pad, then, okay, great,

00:21:05.006 --> 00:21:07.226 A:middle
then they'll put a virtual
D pad on the screen.

00:21:07.976 --> 00:21:11.046 A:middle
But the truth is that this is
usually not really optimal.

00:21:11.316 --> 00:21:13.076 A:middle
These overlays get in the way

00:21:13.076 --> 00:21:15.476 A:middle
of the player seeing
the game field.

00:21:16.226 --> 00:21:18.906 A:middle
And, but more profoundly,
they're indirect.

00:21:19.286 --> 00:21:20.986 A:middle
They're controls
that are controlling

00:21:20.986 --> 00:21:23.566 A:middle
that little paddle that's
going to go underneath.

00:21:23.566 --> 00:21:26.316 A:middle
And, you know, it's a
bouncy ball game, right?

00:21:26.736 --> 00:21:31.566 A:middle
And so since they're indirect,
it relies on the player

