X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:32:57.326 --> 00:33:01.386 A:middle
Okay. So there's a lot of
stuff in "Paddle Mania 3000".

00:33:01.976 --> 00:33:05.266 A:middle
And you know putting all
that together is putting us

00:33:05.266 --> 00:33:08.806 A:middle
over the limit for
downloading over cellular.

00:33:09.246 --> 00:33:10.806 A:middle
So what do you do?

00:33:10.846 --> 00:33:15.556 A:middle
Well, you know, a lot of times,
a discussion will begin, and,

00:33:15.556 --> 00:33:17.786 A:middle
you know, quite often there
will be somebody who will chime

00:33:17.786 --> 00:33:22.006 A:middle
in with advice like this:
"One size fits all!"

00:33:22.546 --> 00:33:23.926 A:middle
Just ship one size.

00:33:23.926 --> 00:33:24.746 A:middle
Stretch it.

00:33:25.136 --> 00:33:27.236 A:middle
Stretch it to fit
on all platforms,

00:33:27.576 --> 00:33:29.616 A:middle
or just ship one localization.

00:33:29.616 --> 00:33:31.316 A:middle
They all speak English, right?

00:33:32.076 --> 00:33:33.626 A:middle
No, they really don't.

00:33:34.696 --> 00:33:37.306 A:middle
So don't sacrifice quality.

00:33:37.526 --> 00:33:40.656 A:middle
And don't shortchange
your global audience.

00:33:41.196 --> 00:33:44.976 A:middle
Realize that what you could
probably get your game

00:33:44.976 --> 00:33:48.596 A:middle
under 100 megabytes if you use
background transfers, you know,

00:33:48.596 --> 00:33:51.686 A:middle
and let the user download
the main bundle of it now

00:33:51.686 --> 00:33:54.026 A:middle
but have more content
that gets transferred

00:33:54.026 --> 00:33:56.056 A:middle
down after they've
run it the first time.

00:33:57.126 --> 00:33:59.406 A:middle
So there's a couple of
things to do this now.

00:33:59.756 --> 00:34:02.336 A:middle
So the first step really is
to take a good solid look


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:59.756 --> 00:34:02.336 A:middle
So the first step really is
to take a good solid look

00:34:02.336 --> 00:34:05.696 A:middle
at your game and the
game design and determine

00:34:05.696 --> 00:34:07.016 A:middle
if there is some content

00:34:07.016 --> 00:34:09.485 A:middle
that isn't really
needed right up front.

00:34:10.206 --> 00:34:12.545 A:middle
And games, especially
games with any kind

00:34:12.545 --> 00:34:16.485 A:middle
of a linear progression are
perfect for this, right.

00:34:16.795 --> 00:34:19.275 A:middle
You put the first couple of
hours or whatever, you know,

00:34:19.275 --> 00:34:23.226 A:middle
the first 20, 30 levels in
the bundle at full quality.

00:34:23.815 --> 00:34:26.696 A:middle
And then that's going to
provide enough time for the user

00:34:26.696 --> 00:34:29.666 A:middle
to be playing, and then you
use background transfers

00:34:29.906 --> 00:34:32.576 A:middle
to download the rest while
their playing those first 20.

00:34:32.576 --> 00:34:34.946 A:middle
So how's this done?

00:34:35.735 --> 00:34:38.966 A:middle
Okay. So NSURLSession is an
API that we introduced back

00:34:38.966 --> 00:34:42.596 A:middle
in iOS 7, and the
use is to upload

00:34:42.596 --> 00:34:44.956 A:middle
and download data
from your own server.

00:34:45.286 --> 00:34:47.676 A:middle
And this is intended
for large data sets.

00:34:47.726 --> 00:34:52.176 A:middle
So game levels, big images,
sound files, texture atlases,

00:34:52.176 --> 00:34:53.565 A:middle
all that kind of thing, right.

00:34:54.196 --> 00:34:58.046 A:middle
Now, the transfer, itself,
happens outside of your process.

00:34:58.046 --> 00:34:58.996 A:middle
You just set it off.

00:34:58.996 --> 00:35:01.096 A:middle
You'll get notified
when it's completed.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:58.996 --> 00:35:01.096 A:middle
You'll get notified
when it's completed.

00:35:01.396 --> 00:35:04.116 A:middle
The player can continue
or the app can even be,

00:35:04.116 --> 00:35:05.946 A:middle
you know, quit or terminated.

00:35:05.946 --> 00:35:07.986 A:middle
And the download is
going to keep on going.

00:35:08.696 --> 00:35:11.276 A:middle
And the app, if it's
running, will be notified,

00:35:11.276 --> 00:35:14.726 A:middle
or it'll be woken up when
the transfer is done.

00:35:15.136 --> 00:35:18.236 A:middle
And it's just enough so that you
can take the content that's been

00:35:18.236 --> 00:35:21.156 A:middle
downloaded and, kind
of, unpack it and put it

00:35:21.156 --> 00:35:22.666 A:middle
into its permanent location.

00:35:23.376 --> 00:35:24.646 A:middle
So it's really useful.

00:35:25.566 --> 00:35:28.456 A:middle
It does obviously, it adds
some complexity, right.

00:35:28.456 --> 00:35:30.926 A:middle
Because you're going to have
to handle some corner cases now

00:35:31.046 --> 00:35:33.736 A:middle
that you didn't have before,
like the player running

00:35:33.736 --> 00:35:37.646 A:middle
out of disk space or, you
know, reaching a level

00:35:37.646 --> 00:35:39.866 A:middle
that you haven't
successfully downloaded yet.

00:35:40.676 --> 00:35:42.346 A:middle
And it's important, also,

00:35:42.346 --> 00:35:44.806 A:middle
that you follow the iOS
Data Storage Guidelines.

00:35:44.896 --> 00:35:46.996 A:middle
So these will tell you exactly

00:35:46.996 --> 00:35:49.986 A:middle
where to put any
downloaded assets.

00:35:50.596 --> 00:35:55.416 A:middle
And also remember, this is about
assets, you know, new textures,

00:35:55.416 --> 00:35:59.166 A:middle
new levels, new sounds, and that
kind of thing, but not code.

00:35:59.616 --> 00:36:02.256 A:middle
If you're making code
changes, that has to go back


